<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="ch3-section-gravitational-force" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Gravitational force</title>

    <p>
        The <term>gravitational force</term> <m>\vec{F}_g</m> [N] is an attractive force between two masses.
        <term>Newton's law of universal gravitation</term> gives the magnitude of the gravitational force:
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-gravitational-force-magnitude" number="yes">
            F_g = G \frac{m_1 \, m_2}{r^2}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        where <m>r</m> [m] is the distance between the centers of masses <m>m_1</m> [kg] and <m>m_2</m> [kg]
        and <m>G = 6.6743 \times 10^{-11}</m> <m>\text{N} \, \text{m}^{2} \, \text{kg}^{-2}</m>
        is the <term>gravitational constant</term>.
    </p>

    <p>
        For an air parcel attracted to Earth by its gravitational force (<xref ref="ch3-gravitational-force" text="type-global" />),
        we can replace <m>m_1</m> with the air parcel's mass <m>m</m> and <m>m_2</m> with Earth's mass <m>M_E</m>.
        Then <xref ref="eqn-gravitational-force-magnitude" text="type-global" /> dictates
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-gravitational-force-earth-r" number="yes">
            \vec{F}_g = -G \frac{m \, M_E}{r^2} \left( \frac{\vec{r}}{r} \right)
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        where <m>r</m> now represents the distance between the air parcel's center of mass and Earth's center of mass
        and <m>\vec{r}</m> points from Earth's center of mass to the air parcel's center of mass.
        (Note <m>\dfrac{\vec{r}}{r}</m> is a unit vector, since <m>|\vec{r}| = r</m>.)
        If we further assume Earth is spherical with radius <m>a</m>, <xref ref="eqn-gravitational-force-earth-r" text="type-global" /> becomes
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-gravitational-force-earth-z" number="yes">
            \vec{F}_g = -G \frac{m \, M_E}{(a+z)^2} \left( \frac{\vec{r}}{r} \right)
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        Dividing <xref ref="eqn-gravitational-force-earth-z" text="type-global" />
        by <m>m</m> produces the gravitational force per unit mass,
        which is called the <term>gravitational acceleration</term>
        <m>\vec{g^*}</m> [<m>\text{m} \, \text{s}^{-2}</m>]:
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-gravitational-acceleration-earth" number="yes">
            \frac{\vec{F}_g}{m} = \vec{g^*} = -G \frac{M_E}{(a+z)^2} \left( \frac{\vec{r}}{r} \right)
        </md>
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ch3-gravitational-force">
        <caption />
        <sidebyside>
            <figure xml:id="ch3-airparcel-earth-gravitational">
                <caption>
                    A wide view of Earth's gravitational force <m>\vec{F}_g</m>
                    attracting the air parcel from <xref ref="ch3-air-parcel" text="type-global" />
                    toward the planet's center of mass.
                </caption>
                <image source="images/ch3-airparcel-earth-gravitational.png" width="50%">
                    <shortdescription>
                        Air parcel attracted to Earth by gravitational force.
                    </shortdescription>
                </image>
            </figure>
            <figure xml:id="ch3-airparcel-gravitational">
                <caption>
                    A zoomed-in view of Earth's gravitational force <m>\vec{F}_g</m>
                    acting on the center of mass of the air parcel from <xref ref="ch3-airparcel-earth-gravitational" text="local" />
                    toward the planet's center of mass.
                </caption>
                <image source="images/ch3-airparcel-gravitational.png" width="50%">
                    <shortdescription>
                        Air parcel attracted to Earth by gravitational force.
                    </shortdescription>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </sidebyside>
    </figure>

</section>